"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346910","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-02","<p>The Ministry of Defence has a range of capabilities which contribute to the Government's overall strategy to counter the Chemical Biological Radiological and Nuclear (CBRN) threat. Defence has a number of programmes in train to enhance its Counter-CBRN capabilities to detect and remove CBRN threats and to protect UK Forces in the event of an attack. Building on existing capabilities, this will deliver a UK response that includes: early warning and detection, individual and collective protection, treatment and post-crisis management, and intelligence and analysis.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2015-06-02T16:19:17.477Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346910/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346910/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346910/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-27","Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what steps he is taking to increase the UK's counter- (a) chemical, (b) biological (c) radiological and (d) nuclear capabilities.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346911","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-02","We continue to track developments in the Western Balkans closely. The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), discussed our concerns about the political situation in Macedonia with EU Foreign Ministers at the Foreign Affairs Council on 18 May, and I met the Foreign Ministers of Macedonia and Albania in the margins of the Council of Europe Ministerial meeting on 18 May. As part of regular contacts with Western Balkans counterparts, we continue to raise regional security concerns.","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2015-06-02T14:15:14.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346911/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346911/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346911/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-05-27","Balkans: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will meet his counterparts in the Balkan countries to discuss reducing tensions between Albania, Kosovo and Macedonia.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346912","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my right hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), has discussed the security situation in the South China Sea with his Chinese counterpart. He has also discussed the issue in other multilateral fora, for instance at the recent G7 Foreign Ministers’ meeting. The Secretary of State for Defence, my right hon. Friend the Member for Sevenoaks (Mr Fallon), highlighted our concerns about the current situation during his speech at the Shangri-la Dialogue in Singapore on 30 May. The UK has a clear interest in regional peace and stability and respect for freedom of navigation. We will continue to make our concerns known.</p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2015-06-04T13:53:05.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346912/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346912/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346912/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-05-27","South China Sea: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, if he will discuss with his Chinese counterpart reducing regional tensions over territorial disputes in the South China Sea.","false","Biography information for Mark Pritchard","The Wrekin","Mark Pritchard","276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346913","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-06-03","<p>This Government is helping to grow the UK’s food and drink industry, which remains the country’s biggest manufacturing sector contributing £103 billion a year to our economy and employing 1 in 8 people.</p><p>Consumers both here and abroad want to buy great British food and drink. We are championing British produce overseas using the GREAT campaign, supporting companies to increase their exports and opening new markets for animal and animal products including poultry, pigmeat and dairy.</p><p>We are encouraging UK producers to raise the profile of unique regional products and boost their sales under the EU Protected Food Name scheme. We are pressing for better country of origin labelling in Europe, particularly for dairy, so that our consumers can identify and buy quality British produce. The Plan for Public Procurement: Food and Catering Services, published in July 2014, guarantees that all central government departments purchase food to British standards of production.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2015-06-03T10:38:59.967Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346913/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346913/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346913/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-05-27","Food: Consumption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she is taking to encourage the consumption of (a) eggs, (b) bacon, (c) chicken and (d) butter.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","72"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346914","Department of Health","false","2015-06-03","<p>Under the Care Act 2014, local authorities must promote wellbeing when carrying out any of their care and support functions in respect of a person. This is sometimes referred to as “the wellbeing principle” because it is a guiding principle that puts wellbeing at the heart of care and support. The definition of wellbeing includes physical and mental health and emotional wellbeing.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Assessments under the Care Act will identify the person’s needs and how these impact on their wellbeing. Care Plans must detail the needs to be met and how the needs will be met, and will link back to the outcomes that the adult wishes to achieve in day-to-day life as identified in the assessment process and to the wellbeing principle in the Act.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has recognised the importance of doing more to consider the mental wellbeing of people in care homes and asked the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) to prioritise this area for one of its first Quality Standards for adult social care which were published in December 2013. The links to these standards can be found here:</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ph16" target="_blank">http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/ph16</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs50" target="_blank">http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs50</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p><a href="http://pathways.nice.org.uk/pathways/mental-wellbeing-and-older-people" target="_blank">http://pathways.nice.org.uk/pathways/mental-wellbeing-and-older-people</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Health and Social Care Act 2008 Regulations 2014 sets out the fundamental standards of care people should expect. Regulation 9 – person centred care, makes clear that; “Providers must make every reasonable effort to provide opportunities to involve people in making decisions about their care and treatment, and support them to do this. This includes physical, psychological or emotional support, or support to get information in an accessible format or to understand the content.”</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The independent regulator, the Care Quality Commission when inspecting services to make sure they meet the fundamental standards of quality and safety, use NICE guidelines and quality standards as evidence to inform its inspection processes and to inform the award of good and outstanding ratings.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>A link to the 2008 regulations can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.cqc.org.uk/content/regulations-service-providers-and-managers" target="_blank">http://www.cqc.org.uk/content/regulations-service-providers-and-managers</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Improving Access to Psychological Therapies Programme, introduced in 2010, offers patients routine NICE approved talking therapies for the treatment of common mental health disorders including anxiety and depression. The programme aims to provide access to at least 15% of those who require treatment by March 2015 (data available July 2015). NHS England is leading work to ensure that older adults and other under-represented groups are encouraged to seek the help that they need.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-03T14:40:41.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346914/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346914/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346914/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Care Homes: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to ensure that residents in care homes have access to therapies to improve their mental wellbeing.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","44"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346915","Department of Health","false","2015-06-04","<p>There have been no discussions between my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and the Royal Colleges about treatment using VEGF-C protein.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-04T15:12:14.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346915/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346915/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346915/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Vascular Endothelial Growth Factor C","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Royal Colleges about treatment using VEGF-C protein.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","73"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346916","Department of Health","false","2015-06-05","<p>The Government has specifically supported the clinical application of stem cells as part of an overall strategy to develop regenerative medicine. Regenerative medicine includes a wide range of cellular therapies including the use of stem cells to promote the regrowth of bone tissue. Regenerative medicine is one of the eight great technologies identified for targeted investment and where the United Kingdom has the potential to become a world-leader. Earlier this year the Regenerative Medicine Expert Group (RMEG) published their final report. This report sets out an NHS regenerative medicine delivery readiness strategy and action plan. The RMEG report sets out a series of recommendations and these will form the basis of the ongoing strategy to support regenerative medicine.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-05T11:50:09.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346916/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346916/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346916/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Bone Diseases: Stem Cells","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to encourage the use of stem cell therapy for bone regrowth.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","45"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346917","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>The available information is provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-02T15:34:45.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346917/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346917/answer","FCEs- mastectomy and breast reconstruction 2009-14.xlsx","FCEs- mastectomy and breast reconstruction 2009-14.xlsx","FCEs- mastectomies & breast reconstruction 2009-14","FCEs- mastectomies & breast reconstruction 2009-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346917/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Mastectomy: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many women in each age cohort have had mastectomies in each of the last five years; and how many of them have had reconstructive breast surgery.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","46"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346918","Home Office","false","2015-06-02","<p>The Government introduced the Psychoactive Substances Bill in the House of Lords on 28 May which provides for a blanket ban on the supply, sale, distribution and production of new psychoactive substances to protect people from exposure to these substances. The Misuse of Drugs Act 1971 provides a robust framework to control new psychoactive substances following assessment by the Advisory Council on the Misuse of Drugs. Since 2010, we have banned more than 500 new drugs, and on 10 April we subjected 5 stimulants to temporary control under the 1971 Act.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-02T14:06:00.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346918/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346918/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346918/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-05-27","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ban legal highs.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","74"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346919","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-01","<p>Work has begun on the 2015 Strategic Defence and Security Review. The Review will consider the changing international and domestic security environment and assess what defence capabilities will address the threats we face.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2015-06-01T16:41:47.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346919/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346919/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346919/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-27","Unmanned Air Vehicles: Strategic Defence and Security Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 23 February 2015 to Question 224466, whether the Strategic Defence and Security Review will address the issues identified in Joint Doctrinal Note 2/11, the UK Approach to Unmanned Aircraft Systems.","true","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346920","Department of Health","false","2015-06-05","<p>There have been no discussions between my Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health and the Royal Colleges about the use of Kisspeptin to treat infertility or diabetes.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-05T11:49:02.36Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346920/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346920/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346920/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Kisspeptin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what discussions he has had with the Royal Colleges about the use of kisspeptin to treat (a) infertility and (b) diabetes.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","75"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346921","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-04","<p>This Government is committed to supporting people’s aspirations to own their own home.</p><p> </p><p>By 31 March 2015, almost 100,000 families have bought a home with the assistance of the Help to Buy schemes in the UK. This includes 27 families in the Bermondsey and Old Southwark constituency and 5,819 families in London.</p><p> </p><p>At Budget 2014, the Chancellor announced that the Help to Buy Equity Loan scheme would be extended to 2020 providing a further £6 billion to support 120,000 more people into home ownership.</p><p> </p><p>Official statistics on Help to Buy: Equity Loan scheme sales, at 31 March in England, broken down by constituency, local authority and postcode, are available at: <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>Official statistics on Help to Buy: Mortgage Guarantee sales, at 31 March, broken down by constituency, local authority and postcode are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-march-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/help-to-buy-mortgage-guarantee-scheme-quarterly-statistics-october-2013-to-march-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Official statistics on Help to Buy: New Buy sales, at 31 March, broken down by local authority are available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/help-to-buy-equity-loan-scheme-monthly-statistics</a>. Figures are not available by constituency.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2015-06-04T16:36:24.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346921/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346921/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346921/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-05-27","Help to Buy Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans his Department has to develop the Help to Buy scheme to ensure it supports people in (a) Bermondsey and Old Southwark constituency, (b) London and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346922","Department for Culture Media and Sport","false","2015-06-04","<p>Current superfast broadband coverage is over 80% of UK premises and the Government remains committed to providing access to superfast broadband for 95% of homes and businesses by December 2017. In areas of the country covered by the Superfast Broadband Programme, projects are managed by Local Authorities who can agree their own priority areas with their supplier. There is no superfast broadband project under the programme in London, but small and medium sized enterprises in London are eligible for grants of up to £3,000 to improve their broadband connections under the Broadband Connection Voucher Scheme.<br></p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-06-04T08:10:27.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346922/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346922/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346922/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-05-27","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what plans his Department has to improve access to high speed internet for people in (a) former dockyard areas and (b) rural communities.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346923","Department of Health","false","2015-06-01","<p>The Human Fertilisation and Embryology Act 1990, as amended, already addresses this technology.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-01T14:03:41.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346923/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346923/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346923/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","In Vitro Fertilisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to bring forward legislative proposals to prohibit embryonic gene-editing technologies developed over the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346924","Home Office","false","2015-06-01","<p>The Home Office does not hold the information requested. The Home Office receives data on notifiable offences recorded by the police in England and Wales, however it is not possible to determine the number of offences that were directed at hunts</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-01T09:38:55.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346924/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346924/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346924/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-05-27","Hunting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many criminal attacks on hunts there have been in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","47"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346925","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2015-06-01","<p>The five councils in the Tees Valley have proposed a combined authority and we are now carefully considering the proposals. An elected mayor is not a pre-condition for a combined authority. My rt. hon. Friend, the Chancellor of the Exchequer has been clear that the transfer of major power to a city will only happen to those cities who have a metro mayor.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2015-06-01T15:52:50.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346925/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346925/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346925/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-05-27","Local Government: Tees Valley","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what progress has been made on creating a Tees Valley combined authority; and whether an elected mayor is a pre-condition for any such authority.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","80"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346926","Department of Health","false","2015-06-01","<p>All National Health Service organisations are expected to comply with their existing obligations for data protection. Organisations that consider sending data overseas must follow existing information governance guidance that includes a comprehensive assessment of the risks and mitigations possible. Such risk considerations should be undertaken on a case by case basis by the NHS organisation concerned and may vary according to the data and overseas locations involved. Use of the standard contract clauses provided by the Information Commissioner should also be made, with appropriate data assurance checks implemented.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-01T14:12:02.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346926/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346926/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346926/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Medical Records: Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what data protection measures are in place when sending patient data to a country that does not appear on the European Commission's list of countries recognised as providing adequate protection.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","81"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346927","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-03","<p>In accordance with section 88 of the Representation of the People Act 1983, the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland will publish the list of candidates’ election expenses for the UK Parliamentary election within 10 days from the deadline for submission of elections expenses. The deadline for submissions is Friday 12 June 2015.</p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2015-06-03T11:59:16.07Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346927/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346927/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346927/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-05-27","General Election 2015: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, when she expects the Electoral Office for Northern Ireland to publish the list of candidates' expenses relating to the recent General Election.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346928","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-06-03","<p>The National Crime Agency became fully operational in Northern Ireland on 20 May. This will boost efforts to combat serious organised crime. However, responsibility for the National Crime Agency in Northern Ireland rests with the devolved Department of Justice, not the Northern Ireland Office.</p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2015-06-03T12:10:17.9Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346928/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346928/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346928/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-05-27","National Crime Agency: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, how many (a) full and (b) part-time personnel will be engaged exclusively in duties for the National Crime Agency in Northern Ireland in the next 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346929","Department of Health","false","2015-06-01","<p>It is a matter for the Scottish Government to decide how to use the apportioned payments they receive from the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS).</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government has no plans to create a New Medicines Fund in England.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government established the Cancer Drugs Fund to ensure that cancer patients in England have better access to life-extending and improving drugs not routinely funded by the National Health Service. Between October 2010 and December 2014 the Fund has helped over 67,000 cancer patients.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Government is implementing all of the commitments in the PPRS on improving access to innovative medicines commensurate with the outcomes they offer patients. In addition, NHS England and the Association of the British Pharmaceutical Industry are pressing ahead with plans to maximise the benefits of the PPRS by improving access to and optimising the use of medicines to improve patient outcomes.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In addition the Accelerated Access Review is looking at a range of proposals for accelerating access to innovative medicines to NHS patients and the potential for securing more value from the NHS research infrastructure in commissioning innovative medicines.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-01T13:57:06.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346929/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346929/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346929/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Drugs: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's policies of plans in Scotland to double the New Medicines Fund; and what his policy is on creating such a fund in England.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","83"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346930","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-04","<p>Income tax relief is available on individual contributions to registered pension schemes. Contributions are subject to a tax charge on any pension savings in excess of an annual allowance (plus any unused allowance from the previous three years). The annual allowance for the present tax year (2015-16) is £40,000. Contributions may also be subject to the lifetime annual allowance. The lifetime annual allowance for the present tax year (2015-16) is £1,250,000.</p><p>Individuals can save up to £15,240 in an ISA (Individual Savings Account) in the 2015-16 tax year. The amount of tax relief that a higher rate taxpayer can receive will depend on the overall returns from the cash and other ISA-eligible assets they hold.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-04T14:36:18.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346930/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346930/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346930/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-05-27","Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the maximum amount is that a higher-rate taxpayer could save in the current financial year only utilising maximum tax reliefs in (a) a personal pension and (b) an ISA.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346931","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-03","<p>This information can be found in the most recent statutory report which the Treasury provided to Parliament as required by Section 2 of the Loans to Ireland Act 2010. The last report was published on the 13 October 2014 and is available here along with all previous reports submitted:<br><br>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/bilateral-loan-to-ireland <br><br>Since the publication of this report, the UK has received a further interest payment from Ireland, on the 15 December 2014, of £41,998,674.42. <br><br>The next report, covering the reporting period which finished on the 31 March 2015, will be provided as soon as reasonably possible.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2015-06-03T16:31:03.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346931/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346931/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346931/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-05-27","Overseas Loans: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the current status is of the previous Government's loan to the government of Ireland; and what proportion of that loan remains outstanding.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346932","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-06-08","<p /> <p>Financial Penalties for aggravated breach of employment law, under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013, were introduced on 6 April 2014. Financial penalties are intended to be used in exceptional circumstances where employers have deliberately flouted the law, and whose behaviour is malicious or negligent.</p><p> </p><p>Three have been imposed to date. One has been paid. The other two are currently unpaid.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2015-06-08T16:41:43.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346932/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346932/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346932/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-05-27","Employment Tribunals Service: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many financial penalties have been imposed on respondent employers under section 16 of the Enterprise and Regulatory Reform Act 2013 to date; and how many such penalties (a) have been paid and (b) remain unpaid.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346933","HM Treasury","false","2015-06-03","<p>According to the latest figures published by the Office for National Statistics, the UK's total household debt was £1,686 billion in the fourth quarter of 2014. As a proportion of household income, household debt has fallen from a peak of 169 per cent in the first quarter of 2008 to 146 per cent in the fourth quarter of 2014.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2015-06-03T16:48:28.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346933/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346933/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346933/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2015-05-27","Debts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the aggregate household debt in the UK on 8 May 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","304"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346934","Ministry of Justice","false","2015-06-02","<p>Following a public consultation, fees were introduced in Employment Tribunals to reduce the burden on the taxpayer of paying for Employment Tribunals and to encourage parties to seek alternative ways of resolving their disputes. <br><br>The Government has ensured that fee waivers are available for those who cannot afford to pay, as well as diverting people away from potentially acrimonious hearings, where possible, through a new early conciliation scheme which has already been used by over 60,000 people in its first six months.<br><br>The Government is currently considering the options for a review of Employment Tribunal fees. A further announcement will be made in due course.<br><br></p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2015-06-02T16:45:57.873Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346934/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346934/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346934/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2015-05-27","Employment Tribunals Service: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when he plans to conduct a review of the effects of the introduction of employment tribunal fees.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","134"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346935","Department of Health","false","2015-06-01","<p>Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme (PPRS) payments for England all go back into spending on improving patients’ health and care. The Department includes the expected PPRS payments in setting the NHS England allocations in advance of each year.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Decisions on how NHS England medicines budgets are spent are taken by NHS England clinical leadership on the basis of clinical priorities.</p><p> </p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2015-06-01T14:15:00.423Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346935/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346935/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346935/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, in what ways the rebate from the Pharmaceutical Price Regulation Scheme has been spent in England; and if he will make it his policy that any future rebate will be allocated for treatments for (a) cystic fibrosis and (b) other long term conditions.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","84"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346936","Department for Education","false","2015-06-02","<p>The changes will be implemented to all working parents of three- and four-year-olds from September 2017. We are also developing plans to introduce the changes for some families a year earlier than planned, in September 2016.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2015-06-02T10:42:32.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346936/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346936/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/346936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2015-05-27","Children: Day Care","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the timetable is for the implementation of 30 hours of free childcare to working parents of three and four year-olds; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","267"
