"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347157","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-04","<p>In July 2013 £4.2million funding was announced to support efforts aimed at increasing the completeness and accuracy of the register. In October 2013 £385,848 of this funding was awarded to 24 successful Electoral Registration Officer (ERO) applicants. The remainder of the funding, as announced on 5 February 2014, was shared between every ERO in Great Britain and five national organisations. Full information is available here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/funding-for-new-ways-to-encourage-voter-registration" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/funding-for-new-ways-to-encourage-voter-registration</a></p><p>In addition almost £10million was invested in 2014/15 aimed at maximising levels of voter registration with £6.8million being shared among every ERO in Great Britain.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-04T11:52:32.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347157/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347157/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347157/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-05-27","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Written Statement of 5 July 2013, Official Report, column 71WS, what proportion of (a) the Targeted Canvassing Fund, (b) the ERO Registration Fund, (c) the Innovation Fund and (d) Schools Outreach has been spent in (i) England, Wales and Scotland combined, (ii) England, (iii) London, (iv) the London Borough of Islington and (v) Islington South and Finsbury constituency to date.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347158","Home Office","false","2015-06-02","<p>To increase awareness of the risks of new psychoactive substances (NPS), the Government has recently introduced the Psychoactive Substances Bill, which will bring in a blanket ban of NPS by prohibiting and disrupting production, distribution, sale and supply in the UK. The Bill will give police and other law enforcement agencies greater powers to tackle the trade in NPS, targeting suppliers who profit from their sale with complete disregard for the potential risks and consequences. The Home Office ran two advertising campaigns in 2013 and 2014 targeted at young people, with the objective to raise awareness of the dangers of NPS and signpost the FRANK website for further information and advice. In March 2015, we published a resource pack, written in partnership with front line practitioners, to enable those working with young people to have conversations with NPS users and challenge their drug use by raising awareness of the risks and consequences. Total spend on this NPS communications activity in 2013 to 2015 was £180,556. From 2010 to 2013, the Home Office ran a national campaign raising awareness of FRANK, the national drug information and advice service. The FRANK website contains information about the dangers of NPS. Every year since 2009, Ministers have written to approximately 50 festival organisers highlighting NPS dangers and calling on them to adopt a ‘no-legal highs’ policy for their festivals</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2015-06-02T16:07:48.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347158/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347158/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347158/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-05-27","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken to increase awareness of new psychoactive substances and their dangers in the last five years; and what the cost of such work has been.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347159","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Electoral Commission will next report on progress with the transition to Individual Electoral Registration (IER) in June 2015. The Commission’s assessment will seek to consider the potential impact of ending the transition to IER in December 2015 to inform the UK Government’s decision on whether to make an Order to bring forward the end of the transition from December 2016.</p>","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter",,"2015-06-03T16:42:32.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347159/answer","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347159/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347159/answer",,,,,"36","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission","2015-05-27","Electoral Register","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for South West Devon, representing the Speaker's Committee on the Electoral Commission, pursuant to the Written Statement of 18 December 2013, Official Report, column 106WS, when he expects the Electoral Commission to make its recommendation as to whether the transition to individual Electoral Registration should conclude in 2015 to 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347160","Home Office","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Government introduced the Psychoactive Substances Bill in the House of Lords on 28 May. This provides for a blanket ban on the production, distribution, sale and supply of new psychoactive substances (NPS), to protect young people from exposure to these new drugs. The Home Office Forensic Early Warning System (FEWS) was set up in January 2011 to bolster national capacity to identify NPS available in the UK. It brings together expertise from forensic laboratories and chemical standard suppliers, UK-wide law enforcement agencies and experts in the field. The system continues to develop a co-ordinated UK-wide approach to laboratory testing and analysis of law enforcement seizures and test purchasing to identify these substances. The number of NPS not previously encountered either in the UK or at EU level, identified by FEWS from January 2011 until March 2014, is not recorded on a monthly basis. The annual figures are set out in the answer to your question of 26 February (PQ 225633). Analysis for 2014/15 will be published in due course. Twenty-two new substances identified under the system up to March 2014 are controlled under the Misuse of Drugs Act 1971, of which one is currently controlled under a temporary class drug order. FEWS continues to enable us to effectively assess the availability of NPS and take appropriate action.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","278","2015-06-03T16:46:30.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347160/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347160/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347160/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-05-27","Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what facilities and resources her Department has to assess the chemical content of suspected new psychoactive substances that are identified in the UK.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347161","Cabinet Office","false","2015-06-03","<p>The Government is currently considering the report's recommendations and will respond in due course.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2015-06-03T11:53:49.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347161/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347161/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347161/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-05-27","Constituencies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to respond to the 8th Report of the Political and Constitutional Reform Committee of Session 2014-15, What next on the redrawing of parliamentary constituency boundaries?, HC 600.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","111"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347162","Ministry of Defence","false","2015-06-01","<p>In accordance with the pledge made by my predecessor, the hon. Member for Broxtowe (Anna Soubry), letters have been sent to serving and non-serving personnel at their last known addresses, informing them of this issue, and explaining the options open to them. This information was also shown internally on the Defence Intranet, and externally on the Defence pages of Gov.uk in May 2015. The Department is considering how best to target the message to reach individuals who may not have received it via either of these routes.</p><p>A total of 22 Service complaints have been received to date. All three Services are assisting serving and non-serving personnel who have submitted requests for further information.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2015-06-01T16:41:19.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347162/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347162/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347162/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2015-05-27","Armed Forces: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many advertisements have been placed and in which publications to advise armed forces personnel of their right to make a complaint following their illegal punishment following the receipt of a police caution in the last year; what the cost of placing such advertisements has been; how many such complaints have been received to date; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mrs Madeleine Moon","Bridgend","Mrs Madeleine Moon","157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347286","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>We recognise the importance of care at home and have identified 800,000 of the most vulnerable patients as part of the Proactive Care Programme.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Virtual wards could provide one way of reducing unplanned admissions by providing the staffing, systems and routines of hospital care in the patient’s own home.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-02T15:52:47.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347286/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347286/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347286/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Virtual Wards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the potential for virtual wards to improve health care delivery.","false","Biography information for Jesse Norman","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","900002"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347685","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>The provision of accident &amp; emergency (A&amp;E) services is a matter for the local National Health Service. We are aware of the proposals being developed locally for an Urgent Care Hub at Kettering General Hospital to address pressures faced by the Trust’s A&amp;E service and are encouraged by the innovative thinking of the local commissioners and close working with local people and their representatives.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-02T16:04:45.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347685/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347685/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Accident and Emergency Departments: Northamptonshire","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what plans he has to improve A&E provision in North Northamptonshire.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","900013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347795","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>7% of people who wanted to see or speak to a general practitioner (GP) within a week were unable to do so.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Latest GP Patient Survey results suggest that less than 2% of patients who want GP appointments attend walk-in centres or accident and emergency departments.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-02T15:21:05.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347795/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347795/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347795/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","General Practitioners: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of people are waiting a week or more to see or speak to a GP; and what assessment he has made of the effects of access to GPs on attendances at A&E departments.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","900024"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347796","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>NHS England will be announcing further details about the implementation of the Five Year Forward View in due course.</p><p>Making the best use of available technologies and cutting administration costs will free up £1.5 billion per year in this Parliament for extra resources for front line patient care.</p><p>The Government's manifesto committed that we would continue to ensure that we have enough doctors, nurses and other staff to meet patients’ needs.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-02T15:21:59.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347796/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347796/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347796/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","NHS: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether the £22 billion efficiency savings identified in NHS England's Five Year Forward View will entail reductions in staff numbers.","false","Biography information for Ian Lavery","Wansbeck","Ian Lavery","900021"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347797","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>Trusts placed in special measures receive tailored support to address their problems. I am pleased to report that seven trusts out of 21 trusts have now exited the regime, having demonstrated sustainable improvements in safety and quality of care.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>In the case of Basildon, I understand that Monitor is working with the Trust to help ensure it returns to a stable financial footing, so that the people of Basildon and Thurrock can receive quality healthcare services on a sustainable basis.</p><p> </p>","South West Surrey","Mr Jeremy Hunt",,"2015-06-02T14:21:07.747Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347797/answer","Biography information for Mr Jeremy Hunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347797/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347797/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Hospitals: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in achieving safety in hospitals in special measures.","false","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","900019"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347798","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>In January 2015, NHS England announced an independent Cancer Taskforce to develop a five-year strategy to improve cancer outcomes, including survival rates. The taskforce published a statement of intent in March and will publish the strategy in the summer. We will work with the National Health Service, charities and patient groups to deliver the new strategy.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2015-06-02T14:20:24.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347798/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347798/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347798/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Cancer: Mortality Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he plans to take to improve cancer survival rates over the next five years.","false","Biography information for Mr John Baron","Basildon and Billericay","Mr John Baron","900023"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347799","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>The Department awards around £100 million of grant funding to voluntary sector organisations across the country, including Cheshire, every year. The voluntary sector makes an important contribution to the delivery of local services. We continue to work with commissioners and the sector to encourage effective partnerships.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-02T15:24:10.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347799/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347799/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347799/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Health Services: Third Sector","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps the Government has taken to support third-sector organisations in delivering health services in (a) Eddisbury and (b) England.","false","Biography information for Antoinette Sandbach","Eddisbury","Antoinette Sandbach","900017"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347800","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>We know that, in hospitals, patient care suffers at weekends because there are fewer consultants present, and some services are not always up and running. This is reflected in mortality rates being significantly higher for patients admitted at a weekend.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>That is why we are determined to ensure that patients can get the same care at weekends as during the week.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2015-06-02T15:15:00.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347800/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347800/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347800/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","NHS: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of how seven-day services will improve patient care.","false","Biography information for Maria Caulfield","Lewes","Maria Caulfield","900022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347801","Department of Health","false","2015-06-02","<p>Good mental health is very important to this Government. Having legislated for parity of esteem, this Government will take mental health as seriously as physical health and hold the National Health Service to account for making progress towards parity of esteem. We have committed to introducing new access and waiting standards and will ensure these are delivered.</p><p> </p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2015-06-02T15:42:34.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347801/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347801/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/347801/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-05-27","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what progress has been made in achieving parity of esteem for mental health services.","false","Biography information for Simon Danczuk","Rochdale","Simon Danczuk","900018"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229486","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2015-03-26","<p><em>It has not proved possible to respond to this question in the time available before Prorogation. Ministers will correspond directly with the Member</em></p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord De Mauley",,"2015-03-26T17:02:38.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229486/answer","Biography information for Lord De Mauley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229486/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-03-25","Rights of Way","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under the provisions of the Deregulation Bill, rights of way officers have a duty to persuade objectors to a footpath deregulation order agreed by a county council to correct an error in the definitive footpath map in order to prevent an appeal to the Secretary of State.","false","Biography information for Lord Skelmersdale",,"Lord Skelmersdale","HL5947"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229487","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-03-26","<p>Lebanon and Tunisia are important partners and both the EU and the UK are committed to supporting them in addressing the problems stemming from crises in neighbouring countries. The UK has contributed over £190 million to support refugee and host communities in Lebanon since the Syria crisis began. In Tunisia we have committed £22 million to support political and economic development since the revolution in 2011. Both countries receive significant EU funding. Tunisia has been allocated up to €886 million from the European Neighbourhood Instrument (ENI) for 2014-2020, and €16 million from the European Instrument for Democracy and Human Rights (EIDHR), the Instrument Contributing to Stability and Peace (IcSP), the Non State Actors programme, the Civil Society Facility and ENI thematic instruments. Lebanon has an allocation of up to €385 million from the ENI for 2014-2020. In addition, Lebanon has been allocated a further €449.4 million in support from both the ENI and the IcSP to help it respond to the effects of the crisis in Syria. The Directorate General of the European Commission for Humanitarian Aid and Civil Protection is also providing €172.3 million for humanitarian assistance in Lebanon, with the EIDHR providing €2.4m for 2014-2017. Both countries can also benefit from long-term loans and risk capital facilities, provided and managed by the European Investment Bank.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-03-26T15:53:25.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229487/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229487/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-03-25","Tunisia and Lebanon","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of the proximity of Tunisia and Lebanon to conflicts in Libya and Syria and the role of those states in hosting refugees, they intend to give priority for aid and investment to those states, in the context of the European Fund for Strategic Investments, the European Union Regional Strategy for Syria, the European Union–Tunisia Action Plan and existing association agreements.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL5948"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229326","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-03-26","<p>The recently published government guidance on cyber security for small businesses encourages companies to consider insurance as part of their approach to managing cyber risk. Cyber insurance is a rapidly developing area with government and the insurance sector publishing a joint report on tackling cyber risks on 23 March 2015. A key component of that report is an agreement that participating insurers will include Cyber Essentials accreditation as part of their risk assessment for small and medium businesses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Cyber Security Guidance for Small Business: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412017/BIS-15-147-small-businesses-cyber-guide-March-2015.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/412017/BIS-15-147-small-businesses-cyber-guide-March-2015.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>Cyber Insurance Report: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-cyber-security-the-role-of-insurance" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/uk-cyber-security-the-role-of-insurance</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-03-26T09:20:14.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229326/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229326/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-03-24","Cybercrime: Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps his Department is taking to raise awareness among small and medium-sized businesses of insurance against cyber-attacks.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","228929"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229327","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2015-03-26","<p>This Government is committed to tackling intellectual property crime and is carefully considering the findings and recommendations of ‘Penalty Fair’, the independent review on criminal sanctions for copyright infringement.</p><p> </p><p>Appropriate next steps may include a public consultation, as recommended in the review, giving rights holders, members of the public and all copyright and internet interest groups the opportunity to provide their views. The implementation of any change would need careful consideration to understand its potential impact.</p>","Wantage","Mr Edward Vaizey",,"2015-03-26T09:20:39.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229327/answer","Biography information for Mr Edward Vaizey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/229327/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-03-24","Internet: Copyright","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, with reference to Penalty Fair, the Intellectual Property Office study of criminal sanctions for copyright infringement available under the Copyright, Designs and Patents Act 1988, what plans his Department has to strengthen the penalties for online copyright infringement.","false","Biography information for Mr John Whittingdale","Maldon","Mr John Whittingdale","228923"
